@*
    About page. Scott's strongest honest card: 25 years, ex-agency, direct. Copy is
    placeholder and heavily his to write, especially the personal narrative. Every claim
    baked in here is BACKED (25 years .NET, agency background, direct, backend depth,
    Jambalam). Do NOT invent biography: employers, schools, hometown, dates. Those are
    marked as prompts for Scott to fill, not written for him.
*@

<section class="section--lede">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">About</p>
        <h1 class="header">Scott Neidig</h1>
        <p class="text lede__text">
            Web and application developer on the Colorado Front Range. I've built .NET
            applications since 2005, and I work directly with businesses and organizations on
            the systems they run on.
        </p>

        @*
            Optional headshot. A face builds trust on an about page, but it's not required and
            it's Scott's to add. Drop the image in wwwroot and uncomment:
            <img class="about__photo" src="~/img/scott.jpg" alt="Scott Neidig" width="240" height="240" decoding="async" />
        *@
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">Background</p>
        <h2 class="title">Where I come from</h2>

        @*
            Bio drafted from Scott's resume (Headless format). Every claim is backed by it:
            Havas Edge + Spinutech (agency .NET), certified nopCommerce developer, API/SQL work,
            version migrations, HIPAA security background, Jambalam + its Azure AI feature, and
            his stated use of AI tools in his workflow. Kept in his voice: plain, no em dashes,
            no hype. Scott's to sharpen. NOTE: says "since 2005" (resume start) not "25 years".
        *@
        <p class="text">
            I've been building web applications since 2005, most of that time in .NET and C#.
            A lot of it was at agencies, Havas Edge and later Spinutech, building and maintaining
            sites and applications for their clients: custom features, nopCommerce plugins,
            database work, version migrations, and production deployments. I'm a certified
            nopCommerce developer, and I've spent years working directly with the people whose
            systems I'm in.
        </p>
        <p class="text">
            It's never been just the front end. I've built REST API integrations, designed and
            maintained SQL Server databases, moved stores across major nopCommerce versions
            without breaking their custom logic, and run deployments through CI/CD. Earlier on I
            did HIPAA security work, checking healthcare applications for vulnerabilities, which
            is a habit of mind I still bring to anything handling real data.
        </p>
        <p class="text">
            Now I work directly with businesses and organizations instead of through an agency.
            I also build and run my own software, including Jambalam, a subscription platform on
            nopCommerce and ASP.NET Core with an AI-powered import feature built on Azure. I use
            AI tools in my daily work to move faster, and I check everything they produce. If you
            have a .NET application that needs looking after, or a store on nopCommerce, that's
            squarely what I do.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section>
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">How I work</p>
        <h2 class="title">Direct, and on the hard part</h2>
        <p class="text">
            No agency layer between you and the person doing the work. I take on the back end,
            the database, the business logic, the parts that actually solve the problem, not
            just the page on top. It's where a real application pulls ahead of a template, and
            it's the work I've done for years.
        </p>
        <p class="text">
            That includes AI where it earns its place. I've built it into a live product,
            Jambalam, as a working feature people use.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section--alt">
    <div class="container container--prose">
        <p class="topper">Proof</p>
        <h2 class="title">See the work</h2>
        <p class="text">
            The clearest picture of what I do is what I've built.
        </p>
        <p>
            <a asp-controller="Work" asp-action="Index">Have a look at my work</a>
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<partial name="_CallToAction" model="@("Want to talk about your project?")" />
